<HL> Sony to Begin Selling VCRs In VHS Format </HL>
<AUTHOR> Jeffrey A. Tannenbaum (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> SNE HIT </CO>
<IN> ELE </IN>
<TEXT>
   After resisting for years, Sony Corp. finally is yielding to pressure to sell VHS-format videocassette recorders. 

   But Sony won't abandon its pioneering Beta format, even though VHS commands at least 90% of world-wide sales for videocassette recorders. 

   In Tokyo, Sony announced plans to sell VHS machines in Europe, starting this spring. 
Initially, the machines won't be made by Sony but will only bear its name. 
Some Japanese newspapers have reported that Hitachi Ltd. will make the Sony-brand machines, and Sony hasn't denied those reports. 

   The company's Sony Corp. of America subsidiary, in Park Ridge, N.J., plans to introduce the VHS machines in late fall. 
"This is complementary to our existing products," says Shinichi Takagi, president of Sony of America's consumer video products division. 
"The only hole I can't cover with the present lineup is the VHS area." 

   It is a gaping hole, one the parent company long refused to address. 
In fact, Sony waited so long that it missed the VHS boom. 
Sales of VHS recorders, the premier growth product in consumer electronics in the 1980s, now are stagnating, largely because 52% of U.S. households -- up from 3% six years ago -- already have VCRs. 

   With its first Betamax model, in 1975, Sony ignited the home-video revolution and created a huge market-though mostly for others. 
In the U.S. alone, manufacturers' sales of VCRs totaled $5.25 billion last year, the Electronic Industries Association says. 

   But Sony failed to persuade some rivals -- notably Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. -- to adopt the same technical standards for home video recorders. 
They brought out the incompatible VHS machines, which prevailed partly because they initially allowed for longer taping. 
Moreover, while videophiles say Beta provides a superior picture, more prerecorded material became available in the VHS format. 

   At a confidential brainstorming session in Rye, N.Y., in December 1983, Sony of America executives saw the handwriting on the wall. 
One former Sony planner recalls their conclusion: "We had lost the format battle, and it was pointless to continue fighting." 
But the parent company continued to hold out. 

   On principle, Sony preferred the superior technology, and it feared alienating the big base of Beta devotees. 
About 25 million Betamax machines are in use world-wide -- about 15% of the estimated 170 million existing home VCRs. 
More recently, Sony professed to see no point in entering a market that has turned fiercely competitive -- with manufacturers proliferating, sales growth lagging and prices tumbling. 
"We don't like to just chase sales volume -- we like to do the more profitable items," Masaaki Morita, chairman of Sony of America, said in October. 

   Now, says Mr. Takagi, there is a point to selling VHS: synergy. 
Some consumers prefer to buy systems of a single brand, so the existence of Sony VHS recorders might help sell Sony television sets. 
Also, dealers have long pressured Sony to sell VHS machines, thinking its name would make for an especially salable item. 

   As for the possibility of turning a profit on VHS machines, Mr. Takagi says he sees little chance at the low end of the market, where many companies churn out essentially similar commodities. 
But Sony will seek to develop new features and special designs. 
"There should be a way to make this business a little profitable," he says. 
Because of the dollar's decline, Japanese makers are having trouble earning a profit in the U.S. 

   In Tokyo, Sony said its VHS machines "will be designed to interface with other Sony video and audio products in order to provide for the smooth integration of editing, remote control and connection functions." 
That might allow users of 8mm camcorders, for example, to make VHS copies of their tapes to send to people with only VHS players. 

   No details are yet available on Sony-brand VHS machines to be offered in the U.S. Sony's existing Betamax recorders bear U.S. prices of $300 to $1,300. 

   Meanwhile, Sony says it will continue to develop and promote two other formats: an upgraded Beta version called extended-definition Beta and the 8mm camcorder format. 

   Mr. Takagi says Sony hasn't any plans to sell the enhanced VHS format called Super VHS, which many of its rivals are now introducing. 
Since prerecorded Super VHS material isn't yet available, he notes, there isn't much demand for Super VHS machines. 
In any case, Sony hopes its extended-definition Beta format will win the market for enhanced home recordings. 

</TEXT>
