<HL> Portable VCR-TVs Seek To Be Next Consumer Hit </HL>
<AUTHOR> Stephen Kreider Yoder (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> SNE MC HIT </CO>
<IN> ELE PUB FLX </IN>
<DATELINE> TOKYO  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prepare for the next round of the video wars. 

   The opponents are familiar archrivals Sony Corp. and Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., Japan's biggest consumer-electronics concern. 
The new weapons are portable videocassette recorders with tiny, built-in televisions. 
The Japanese media has already dubbed the imminent fight "Video War Three." 

   On Wednesday, Matsushita unveiled a video recorder-television, weighing slightly more than three pounds, that has a three-inch diagonal color screen. 
The company is pitting its product against Sony's Video Walkman, a nearly 2 1/2-pound model that Sony plans to begin selling in Japan later this month. 

   "It's going to be a hit product," says Keiichi Maesato, an analyst at James Capel Pacific Ltd. 
"And it could well be another war between the formats." 

   Initially, that war will be played out on Japanese soil, where cramped houses and long train commutes from the suburbs of most major cities make the machines a good bet, some analysts say. 
These new recorder-televisions could do for video what Sony did for the stereo cassette player, suggests an analyst at Daiwa Securities Research Institute. 
"It could very well become another Walkman," he says. 
"Businessmen will be watching movies on the trains." 

   The products aren't expected to arrive in the U.S. until sometime next year at the earliest. 
Matsushita will begin selling its new recorder-television in Japan in October, a spokesman says, but won't start selling it overseas -- under its Panasonic nameplate -- until "next year or later." 

   Meanwhile, other electronic giants, such as Toshiba Corp. and Hitachi Ltd., are expected to enter the recorder-television market. 
Matsushita, which is called MEI in Japan, "is like IBM," says Mr. Maesato of James Capel. 
"Other consumer electronic companies wait for MEI," then follow quickly. 

   That pattern has been all too familiar for Sony. 
Known for pioneering many successful consumer products, Sony was first to market a successful home video recorder when it sold its Betamax in 1975. 
But close behind was Victor Co. of Japan, the Matsushita subsidiary that countered with its VHS-format video recorders in 1976. 
VHS recorders proceeded to dominate the market. 
Sony effectively conceded defeat when it announced its own VHS machine last January. 

   When Sony fired the next salvo, its 8mm video camera, JVC was close behind with a competing product that uses VHS-C format tapes, which don't fit in Sony's machines. 
Backers of the competing formats -- which use cartridges roughly the size of audio cassettes -- currently are fighting out what the Japanese media are calling "Video War Two." 

   For the third video war, Sony and Matsushita have combined those cartridges with the latest generation of tiny TVs -- flat, liquid-crystal display screens about the size of a credit card. 
Sony's new Video Walkman uses an 8mm-tape and will sell in Japan for 128,000 yen ($965). 
Matsushita's version, called the Maclord AV Gear, uses VHS-C tape and will sell for 188,000 yen ($1,417). 

   A few movie distributors in Japan are already dubbing films on the 8mm-format. 
Publishing concerns plan to market video versions of business and music magazines for the gadgets. 
Many Japanese, the argument goes, would rather watch their magazines than read them. 

</TEXT>
