<LEADPARA>  VIDEO equipment tops many Christmas lists, so this is a good time to pinpoint
standout designs and good values.;   Camcorders continue to be the most
popular video items. Even in a troubled economy, their sales soar, despite
list prices that start about $1,000. Many novice videographers prefer the
VHS-C format, which combines compactness and compatibility. Tapes made with
these camcorders can be played in any standard VCR after they are placed in an
adapter shell.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CAMCORDERS STILL TOP EQUIPMENT WISH LIST  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  VIDEO  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Among the least expensive models of this type is Panasonic's PV-21 ($999),
which offers an ingenious refinement known as electronic image stabilization.
This automatically compensates for camera jitter resulting from unsteady hands
and also lets you shoot from a moving car without jiggling the picture. In
effect, it places a phantom tripod under the camera.;   Another remarkable
model in the VHS-C format is the JVC GR-AX10U ($1,199), which is so
light-sensitive that it can be used to make videos by candlelight.;   Most
compact camcorders now operate in the 8mm format. These cassettes do not fit
into standard home VCRs; they are played by plugging the camcorder into a VCR
or TV set by means of a simple connecting cable, with the camcorder itself
serving as a playback device.;   The advantage of this system is that it can
record up to two hours per cassette (as compared to 30 minutes in VHS-C)
without sacrificing image quality or compactness. Moreover, the sound in the
8mm format is generally far better. Good values in this group include RCA's
Pro860 ($999) and Sony's CCD-TR51 ($1,200), which is one of the smallest and
lightest camcorders. They would be a preference for those experienced with
video.;   Excellent models in the Hi8 format are Sony's TR-81 ($1,500) and
RCA's Pro880HB ($1,749). In a class by itself is the ultra-sophisticated Canon
L1 ($2,999), the first compact camcorder with interchangeable lenses and
near-professional capabilities. JVC's GR-S505U ($1,599), at 2 1/2 pounds, is a
highly capable and lightweight camcorder in the Super-VHS-C format.;   Editing
equipment is an ideal Christmas present for video fans who already own a
camcorder. The Videonics DirectED Plus ($599), for instance, performs
electronic editing similar to the cutting and splicing of film.;   Much
interest is focused on videodisc players these days. Offering a picture
greatly superior to video cassettes, many quality-conscious video watchers are
now adding laser disc players to their lineup of video components.;   Most of
these so-called omni-players play both audio CD's and videodiscs and thus
serve efficiently in combined audio-video systems. Lower prices have also
contributed to their growing popularity. Sony's MDP-333 ($650) and Yamaha's
CDV-1700 ($699) are economy models notable for their high technology.  </TEXT>
