<LP>
   NEW YORK -- In 1990, camcorders sold at a record pace:
Dealers bought three million, 30% more than the year before.
The consumer electronics industry, which had been fighting
stagnant sales, thought it had found one of those rare "hot"
products, the sort that would surely sell at double-digit
rates well into the 1990s.
   But the hovering recession has slowed purchases of
big-ticket items, and the average retail price for the
lightweight video cameras still hovers around $850. Most
industry executives expect 1991 sales to be flat.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As a result, camcorder makers are rethinking their
approach. Some now worry that the easiest market -- young
parents and newlyweds -- may already be saturated, and they
question just how big the potential camcorder market really
is. "Remember the old generation of super 8 home movie
cameras your father used?" asks Stan Hametz, general manager
of consumer video for Panasonic Co., a unit of Matsushita
Electric Industrial. "They never reached beyond 35% of the
population."
   Manufacturers realize they have to find new markets beyond
Young Parents With Dog or Cat. "If the makers can convince
people it's a replacement for the still camera, to be used by
all age ranges, that will extend the life of camcorders,"
says Clark Johnson of NPD Group, a market research company.
   From the camcorder's introduction in 1983 until this year,
sales growth had been strong. But the devices can be found in
only 14% of U.S. homes (in Japan, penetration has reached
20%). Color TV sets, by contrast, are in 97% of U.S. homes,
and VCRs are used in 74%.
   Some executives say that means a huge, untapped audience
awaits. The question is how to get all those people to buy.
About 43% of camcorder owners are parents under 45 years old
with children living at home, according to the Photo
Marketing Association. A puny 3.9% of camcorder buyers are
young singles; only 5.9% are retired older couples.
   To reach new customers, camcorder marketers are
redesigning their products to play down snazzy technology and
cut down on the profusion of push buttons. Some brands are
pitching new business uses, and others are boosting their
sales help to demystify their products for wary customers.
   But manufacturers are still resisting making prices much
more attractive. Even as they reduced prices and scrambled to
unload high warehouse inventories before Christmas, major
brands stubbornly stayed in the $700 range for their
stripped-down models.
   Sony Corp., most often the premium price leader and the
market leader, led off a round of price-cutting in September
by twice slashing the tag on models in its "family series,"
bringing the lowest retailer-advertised price on a Sony
camcorder to $699. Thomson S.A. followed by chopping $100 off
the prices of a pair of RCA 8mm camcorders, and others, such
as Canon Inc.'s U.S. subsidiary, were forced to follow.
   "It's no mystery that a premium-priced camcorder in this
recession is going to be a difficult purchase," says Alan
Czeizler, a sales director in Canon U.S.A.'s video division.
"We need something to spice up the pot and make it a bit more
appetizing."
   So far the price cuts haven't been enough. Sales of
videocassette recorders exploded when prices fell to the $200
to $300 range. "If adult penetration is to reach 75%, the
price {of camcorders} will have to come below $500," contends
Tom Adams, an analyst with Paul Kagan Associates. "When that
happens, camcorders will open up to a whole new group."
   Yet camcorder makers are balking. "A $500 price doesn't
reflect the real cost of the machine. A more reasonable price
is $799 to $999," says Panasonic's Mr. Hametz. Others say the
actual costs can't be all that much higher than for a VCR,
which contains many of the same features and semiconductor
chips. The fat, they say, is in the profit margins, which are
considerably better than those for more mature products like
compact-disk players and cassette-tape decks -- for
manufacturers and retailers alike.
   In searching for a new kind of customer, Sony has been the
most obvious with its ad campaign for the Handycam line. In
its "Fun Day" spots, a voice intones, "Between the weddings
and the birthdays comes the rest of your life," as a young
urban couple frolics -- and films -- with nary a baby
stroller in sight.
   "In the past, the ads were all about kids, babies,
weddings and bar mitzvahs," says Larry Barruch, Sony's vice
president of advertising in its consumer products group. "We
wanted to show this can be fun at other times."
   Other rivals aren't straying far from the core market of
young parents. "We've tried some senior-market magazine
advertising, and we've tried some other things," says Canon's
Mr. Czeizler. "But the ideal demographic for us is still a
pregnant woman walking into a store to look at a camera."
   In selling to the first wave of camcorder customers -- the
"early adapters" who relish owning the newest high-tech
gadgetry -- manufacturers played up new features year after
year. Panasonic pushed "digital electronic image
stabilization," which eliminates a shaky camera picture.
Canon offered camcorders that can exchange lenses with a 35mm
still camera. Makers also played up their drive for
miniaturization. Earlier this year, Sony proudly unveiled the
world's lightest camcorder, 1.3 pounds, only to be bested two
weeks later by a 1.28-pound Canon model.
   But such wizardry doesn't necessarily attract potential
buyers in the next wave. Acknowledging that, Mitsubishi
Electronics America Inc. plans to introduce a line of VHS-C
camcorders with fewer and bigger buttons at the Consumer
Electronics Show in Las Vegas next month. Its instruction
book will be shortened and rewritten.
   Makers are also pushing new uses. Sony has just begun
selling the "V Box" through computer dealers. Aimed at
businesses and selling for $399, it adds full-motion video to
computer software. Last year Sony introduced the Color Video
Printer for $1,200. It makes snapshot-like color prints from
videos.
   But potential buyers can be confused by the three camera
formats, 8-millimeter, VHS and VHS-C. Many people still
think, wrongly, that an 8mm tape can be played on a VHS
videocassette recorder. To change that, Panasonic sent
"demonstrators" to retailers like Sears and Circuit City to
explain which format does what. Early results show that at
those stores, camcorder sales jumped.
   Sony dominates the 8mm format, which was introduced in
1984 and is the fastest-growing segment, accounting for 52%
of the market. The tapes are the size of audio cassettes and
give a crisper image than VHS, but they must be played back
through a camcorder hooked up to a TV set.
   The more bulky VHS format has fallen to 33% of the market
and is drifting lower; it uses paperback-book-sized tapes,
which can play directly on a VCR. A third format, VHS-C,
holds about 15% of the market and plays smaller VHS cassettes
that can be dropped into cassette adapters that play in a
standard VCR.
   Sony's spending on marketing indicates it wants to
continue its role as market leader. It is outspending the
next biggest media spender, Canon, 3 to 1; for the 12 months
ended in June, Sony spent $18 million, according to Leading
National Advertisers.
   But Sony is still uncertain where its campaign is headed
in 1992. Camcorders now get more corporate advertising
dollars than its Trinitron TV or Walkman lines, but Mr.
Barruch says he is conducting focus groups to figure out what
approach to use in 1992. "We are looking to see," he says,
"what will stimulate people to buy."
</TEXT>
