<HL> Your Money Matters:
Better VCRs and Solar Briefcases: A Walk
Through the Consumer Electronics Show
---
By Jeffrey A. Tannenbaum
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 06/02/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> SNE RCOT MC
ELECTRIC, ELECTRONICS, APPLIANCES (ELE) </IN>
<DATELINE> CHICAGO  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Videocassette recorders. 
Compact-disk players. 
Camcorders. 
Waves of new products have lifted sales of consumer-electronics products to $28.72 billion at factory level last year from $6.74 billion a decade earlier. 

   With growth receding now, the industry sorely needs new splashes. 
One candidate, digital audio tape recorders, has won much notice. 
So have new compact disks with pictures as well as sound. 
Here's a sampler of other items at the summer Consumer Electronics Show. 

   ---
   Personal-stereo fans will be courted with "personal video." 

   Sony Corp., which gave the world the Walkman, says millions of Americans will someday bop around with all-in-one devices that shoot and record video pictures, as well as receive TV signals, and play them on 2.7-inch liquid-crystal screens. 
The Japanese company's U.S. unit is showing a prototype -- without the camera -- that's about eight inches wide and resembles some portable radios; a production model may be sold next year. 

   Meanwhile, Sony will sell a camcorder that weighs less than three pounds, and miniature playback decks, including a desktop model with a five-inch TV screen attached. 
The camcorder will initially list at $1,650. 
But marketers claim trend-setting customers aren't fazed by high prices. 

   ---
   High-resolution VCRs provide much sharper pictures. 

   For example, fine detail of flowers and leaves -- not seen on standard videotapes -- shows up, the result of improved VHS technology. 
Of two rival formats for today's video recorders -- Beta and VHS -- the latter commands most of the market. 
Now, Victor Co. of Japan and its licensees think VHS owners will trade up to a new format called Super VHS, despite initial list prices of $1,200. 
That's at least a $400 premium on the new machines, available in July. (Beta's developer, Sony, also has an improved format-extended-definition Beta in the works.) 

   Old VHS tapes look the same on Super VHS machines, but newly recorded tapes produce a picture with more than 400 horizontal lines, compared with 240 or so for VHS. 
One catch: Most TV sets display 330 or fewer lines, though some new models go up to 560. 
Another: Super-VHS recordings aren't yet available. 

   ---
   Beware the bureaucrat: Rubber stamps are going electronic. 

   A $229 calculator comes with extra keys to write messages -- of up to 1,800 characters, and twice that many with a $35 accessory. 
Using heat-transfer technology, the messages can be stamped onto paper from an inked tape at the bottom of the hand-held device. 
The product -- available next January from Casio Computer Co. of Japan's U.S. unit -- is named HandyWriter. 

   ---
   "Wireless" speakers make home stereo systems handier. 

   New York-based Recoton Corp. will sell speakers that come with an electronic transmitter to be wired between the speakers and any stereo-sound source. 
The speakers will work if plugged into any electrical outlet on the same transformer as the transmitter. 
The wires between speakers and sound source are eliminated, so the speakers can be easily played in any room of the house or on the patio. 
The device and two speakers will cost $250 retail and be available in September. 

   ---
   High-powered executives may soon carry briefcases with solar power. 

   Samsonite Corp., a division of Chicago-based Beatrice Corp., is showing a plastic briefcase with a solar panel riveted to the side. 
The panel produces electricity that charges any rechargeable batteries carried inside the briefcase; Samsonite says the power is sufficient to run a cellular telephone all day. 
Peter G. Dulka, a sales manager, says the product is available "on special order" at a wholesale price of about $300. 

   ---
   Telephones just don't look like telephones any more. 

   For example, Panasonic Co., a unit of Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. of Japan, has a portable model about as small as a pack of king-size cigarettes. 
"For all intents and purposes, it's like the Star Trek communicator," says Michael J. Troetti, a Panasonic sales manager. 
It will be available in September for about $200. 

   For people who want something larger, Panasonic offers a telephone attached to an answering machine, copier and facsimile-transmission device. 
It will list for about $2,000 and reach stores in August. 

   ---
   These gadgets can help you organize your gadgets. 

   First, learn a buzzword: "home-automation system." 
One version -- aimed at running all the electronics in a house from a single push-button telephone -- will cost $1,200 to $8,000, depending mostly on the size of the house. 
The marketer is Mitsubishi Electric Sales America Inc., a unit of Mitsubishi Electric Corp. of Japan. 
Sitting at the phone, the user could operate audio and video equipment, burglar alarms, appliances, telephones, lights and more. 
Initial deliveries are set for December. 

   Also new is a $199 device billed as "the most intelligent component ever designed." 
The unit can control all remote-control equipment -- such as TVs, stereos, satellite dishes, VCRs, compact-disk players and security devices. 
The designer is Steve Wozniak, who was a founder of Apple Computer Inc. and whose new company is named CL9. 

   ---
   Last but not least: a television that costs more than a Mercedes. 

   It even makes owners of Kloss Video Corp.'s $4,295 TV sets look like pikers. 
It's a projection model -- from Mitsubishi -- powerful enough to fill a movie screen with a nearly 17-foot diagonal. 
Mitsubishi has just two U.S. orders so far; deliveries will begin in August. 
Most customers are expected to be corporations, but the company thinks that "a select few" individuals also may want one. 

   The price: $50,000. 

