<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Video Christmas, Or, How To Spend $1,500 Without Half Trying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuck on what to buy this Christmas?
   Make it video!
   Whether you want to splurge, spree, invest or just stuff a few
stockings, here are some wonderful items to buy and some excellent
excuses for buying them.
   SPLURGE:
   A new television set with a 27-inch screen.
   If you're a typical American, you've been watching that 19-inch
tube for more than a few years while new technology has been making
it obsolete.
   This is no time to wait for High Definition TV. The best
estimates put HDTV at least five years away from the expensive end
of the marketplace and maybe even longer before it's affordable in
the mass consumer market.
   Japanese manufacturers are designing video and audio circuitry
that tweaks the TV signal for all it's worth. They make ``enhanced
definition'' with much sharper pictures, even if you live in an
area where cable TV isn't available everywhere. Much of the
broadcast soundtrack in major U.S. cities is in hi-fi stereo, so a
tinny little speaker just isn't going to make it for the 1990s.
   An ``inexpensive'' 19-inch set costs about $200 in a discount
house. It's about $400 for a 19-inch TV loaded with the new
technology, and about $700 for a low-end, high-tech 27-inch tube.
   In areas where such electronic goods are heavily discounted, you
can shop around and get a stunning, stereophonic ``cable-ready'' TV
set for less than $1,000. We're talking automatic tuning, inputs
for multiple video sources, outputs to your home stereo, a
``smart'' remote control and a picture that'll knock your eyes out.
Go for it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SPREE:
   A combination LaserDisc and compact disc player.
   If you haven't already taken the plunge into digital audio for
your home stereo, you should. Compact discs don't wear out and make
any stereo system sound startlingly better. The budget-minded
approach is to buy a small portable unit to start, then trade up to
a full-featured model. But if you've got some Christmas money to
throw around, why not get into digital audio with a machine that
also plays videos? They cost around $500 in the discount houses,
but the LaserDisc image is said to be 60 percent sharper than the
best VHS player and the sound quality is just like a CD.
   Newly released LaserDiscs are sometimes cheaper than VHS tapes.
A VHS new release that retails for $89.95 is in the video disc rack
for $49.95, and some may sell for $29.95. And in theory LaserDiscs
don't wear out and the digital signal will never become obsolete.
   Also, there are certain features you can't get with a VCR, such
as ``letterbox'' formatting that allows you to see the wide screen
image.
   In the ``full-feature'' LaserDisc format, the producers include
incredibly comprehensive supplementary material. The three-disc
package for the 1936 classic musical ``Showboat'' includes excerpts
from the 1929 Universal film version, excerpts of Ziegfield's 1932
Broadway revival, interviews with stars, a color film documentary
on showboats, a visual essay of 300 stills tracing the history of
showboats and the history of the musical on stage, screen and
radio, and enough other archival material to choke a librarian.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   INVEST:
   _A VHS player.
   Not a recorder, mind you, but a transportable, play-only machine
that can run off a 12-volt car, boat or RV system and is about half
the size and half the cost of a videocassette recorder.
   It's great to have a backup when your main VCR breaks down. It's
great to have a portable VCR when you're on vacation or out of the
country. You have to look for these, but they're available at most
video dealers and start at around $150.
   _A four-head, hi-fi, Super VHS videocassette recorder. Or, at
the very least, a stereo VCR that you can pipe through your home
audio system.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   STOCKING STUFFERS:
   _A non-abrasive VCR head cleaner. Use it only when you have
significant deterioration in picture quality. Tape heads are
delicate, precision devices and should not be messed with.
   _Blank tapes. People never have enough blank tapes and they
never buy themselves high quality tapes.
   _Videocassette storage racks. People never have enough places to
store videocassettes, which need and deserve a safe, dust-free
resting place.
   _A year's worth of cable TV service. Surprisingly affordable.
Gift certificates are available. Call your local cable company for
details.
   _Videocassettes. Most people are surprisingly reluctant to buy
themselves their favorite movies, and you usually know what your
friends and relatives enjoy, from ``Teen-age Mutant Ninja Turtles''
to rock concert videos, operas and great games of the World Series.
   Even better, the emergence of big retail video chains and the
plethora of available programming has pushed down the price of
video software.
   Suprisingly, the monster hits of recent years are most heavily
discounted. ``Batman,'' the summer megahit, is couponed, rebated
and generally knocked down to less than $20. ``Who Framed Roger
Rabbit'' lists for about $20; ``E.T. The Extraterrestrial'' is
about $25. ``The Right Stuff'' lists for around $30, and the newly
restored version of ``Lawrence of Arabia'' is $40.
   There's also an abundance of competitively priced,
Christmas-oriented programming in video stores at this time of the
year, from old favorites such as Irving Berlin's ``Holiday Inn'' to
cartoons that will hose down the kids late on Christmas Day.
   _LaserDiscs. Any great film makes for a great disc, and most are
digitally remastered to take advantage of the technology. ``Blade
Runner'' is a big favorite; so are ``Gone With the Wind'' (cropped
back down to its original format and its colors restored) and ``The
Godfather.'' But the hit pick for Christmas giving has to be
``Lawrence of Arabia.''
   The 1962 Academy Award-winning film was restored from its
original negatives under the supervision of director David Lean,
who added 20 minutes of footage cut from the original release. The
standard CLV ($49.95) and the extended play (3 discs, $124.95 list)
contain copious supplementary material.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOME VIDEO DON'Ts:
   _Don't buy for video collectors without very specific knowledge
or instruction. Either they'll already have it, they'll quibble at
the quality of the recording or the format, or they'll say they
only wanted ```Ishtar,' any format, man.''
   Buy them a can of compressed air for blowing dust out of their
machines or a spray bottle of glass cleaner and no-lint paper
towels. Buy them a videocassette rewinder (battery-powered, $29.95
at Radio Shack) or a bulk eraser to get rid of unwanted recordings.
   _Don't forget to buy ``Instant Fireplace,'' at $9.95 _ the
logical culmination of a television culture. Put the cassette in
the VCR. Punch ``play.'' Watch the video of fire burning in
fireplace. Listen to the appropriate music. Wonder about the
decline of the West.
</TEXT>
