<LEADPARA>  Q I keep hearing that CDs wear out. Now I hear that the new CD-ROM computer
disks are particularly vulnerable to decay, because computers can't ignore
missing data the way audio CD players do. Should I go back to 78 rpm records
and punch cards?;   A Contrary to all the rumors that keep surfacing, CDs do
not decay or rot. CDs have not existed long enough to state their life
expectancy conclusively. However, laboratory tests indicate at least 20 years
of life. Many discs in my personal collection are going on 10 years and still
sound great.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SCRATCH A CD, AND YOU MAY FIND DAMAGE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  AUDIO VIDEO  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Two things all CD users (whether audio or computer) should know: First, not
all CDs are manufactured to the same quality standards. Cheap or shoddy
manufacturing practices result in CDs that may deteriorate. Just as there were
good- and bad-quality LPs, some companies make better CDs than others.;  
Second, you can damage a CD. From early CD hype, many people think CDs are
indestructible. Any substance applied to the label side or any scratches on
the label side will damage the data layer beneath. Contrary to what seems
obvious, the silvery side is more immune to damage than the label side. Keep
fingerprints, labels and all writing instruments away from both sides of your
discs. Store them in an environment cooler than 150 degrees Fahrenheit, and
treat them with respect. They should last a lifetime and age less than you
do.;   Q A little while ago you wrote about all the features that a video
camcorder should and should not have. Could you please run that information
again?;   A Most camcorders now have the same features. We recommend compact
8mm or VHS-C over full-size VHS. An 8x zoom is ideal. Many models now come
with 10x zoom, which amplifies jitter and body movement in small handheld
camcorders. Light sensitivity of 5 lux suffices. Many camcorders advertising
sensitivity of better than 5 lux (meaning a smaller number, such as 1 lux)
record barely viewable videos at such a low light level. Remember, even with
the best of camcorders, you'll need at least 100 lux for good-quality videos.
Any camcorder you choose should be easy to hold and easy to operate. The
high-speed shutter feature is not essential. If you desire it, two or three
shutter speeds are adequate. A real-time counter that shows either remaining
or elapsed tape time is very useful. With VHS-C camcorders, hi-fi stereo sound
is highly desirable, especially if you plan to record at the slow EP speed.
Stereo is not standard with 8mm, but the system records in hi-fi.;   Test the
autofocus while at the store. A slow or inaccurate autofocus will cause you
considerable frustration with your camcorder. Also check the zoom speed. Most
good camcorders zoom at dual speeds for greater versatility.;   When shopping,
compare look-alike brands. Panasonic and Sony manufacture camcorders for many
other companies. Often these nearly identical models from a competitor may
cost less because of varying price structures.;   Q While I was out browsing
recently, the Canon A1 Digital Hi8 camcorder caught my attention. The store
had it very attractively priced. Its myriad features amused me. I currently
own a 2-year-old full-size VHS Matsushita-built Montgomery Ward model. It
still does a good job, but can't match the features the Canon offers. I like
the convenience of using regular VHS tape. Doesn't using an 8mm camcorder to
play and rewind prerecorded tapes add to the machine's wear? My brother told
me that he heard from an electronic technician that 8mm camcorders are harder
and more costly to fix. Is this true? Should I trade my old VHS camcorder for
the new Canon?;   A Let's dispel some misconceptions first. Size, not system,
often determines repair costs. An 8mm camcorder is not inherently more
difficult to repair than any other type. However, a camcorder such as the
Canon has a lot more inside it and is much more sophisticated than your
Montgomery Ward model. You can buy a $30 tape winder (available at Radio Shack
or by mail order from ads in video magazines) to wind your tapes if you're
worried about camcorder wear. Winding tapes in any VCR, whether it be Beta,
VHS or 8mm, wears out the mechanism.;   Your Montgomery Ward model is a good,
basic camcorder. It has standard VHS resolution of 240 lines. The Canon A1
digital is a superb camcorder. Its nearly 400 line Hi8 resolution results in a
far superior picture. This Canon, one of the three most feature-laden models
on the market, performs flawlessly. The question is whether you need all these
features.  </TEXT>
