<HEAD>VCR Maker Challenges MCA Buyout on Antitrust Grounds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arizona consumer electronics firm has
filed an antitrust lawsuit to block the merger of MCA Inc. and
Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., claiming they are conspiring to
sabotage sales of its videocassette recorders.
   The federal suit, filed in Phoenix, contends Matsushita's $6.6
billion purchase of MCA violates antitrust law.
   Matsushita denied the allegations in a statement that said: ``We
have only had time for a brief review of the material. However,
even on the basis of our brief review it is apparent the suit is
totally without merit.''
   The suit was filed by Go-Video Inc., a Scottsdale, Ariz.,
company which has marketed a videocassette recorder that can record
two TV programs at the same time or play one tape while recording
another.
   Talk that Matsushita needs MCA to stay competitive after
arch-rival Sony Corp. purchased Columbia Pictures Entertainment
Inc. is a smokescreen, said attorney Joseph Alioto.
   Alioto has represented Go-Video in a series of actions
contending Matsushita, Sony and other Asian companies want to shut
out all U.S. consumer electronics makers. He said he'd taken more
than 70 depositions in Japan over a three-month period that support
that allegation.
   ``We know that if you control the software, you cnntrol the
hardware. ... Except for Go-Video, they already have a monopoly in
the hardware. This is to make sure guys like us don't get in,''
Alioto said.
   He said the Japanese companies intend to use their domination of
both sides of the entertainment business to ensure that
``Go-Video's products will not play their software, and anybody
else (outside Japan) who makes HDTV won't either.''
   The primary objective of the Japanese companies is to dominate
the high-definition television market, Alioto said in a telephone
interview from San Francisco.
   Buying MCA gives Matsushita movies, television shows and
recordings to complement its consumer electronics products. By
controlling both, the company assures itself a ready supply of
programming compatible with any technological improvements that
emerge.
   The strategy was much discussed last year when Sony purchased
Columbia Pictures for $3.4 billion. Many analysts believe that
Sony's Beta format for VCRs might have prevailed over Matsushita's
VHS if Sony had owned Columbia when the Beta format first came out.
   Go-Video already is pursuing its conspiracy claim in an earlier
lawsuit against Matsushita and its Panasonic division; Victor Co.
of Japan Ltd. and its JVC Corp. subsidiary; Sanyo Electric Co.
Ltd.; Sony; and NEC Corp.
   Go-Video contends those companies, unable to develop a machine
that can compete with Go-Video's, conspired to block marketing of
it and have formed a cartel to control such products as
conventional VCRs, digital audio-tape recording equipment and
high-definition television.
   Go-Video is seeking more than $1 billion from the companies in
that action, originally filed in 1987. It settled part of the suit
out of court for $2 million. The suit originally named 14 Japanese
and South Korean companies, as well as the Motion Picture
Association of American.
</TEXT>
