   TOKYO -- Sony Corp. and Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.
-- longtime enemies in the home videotape wars -- said they
will work together to develop a next-generation machine.
   The two Japanese consumer electronics giants, joined by
Hitachi Ltd., said they have agreed on common specifications
for a videocassette recorder compatible with high-definition
television sets. The companies said in a statement they "will
now work together to introduce this format to domestic and
overseas industries."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The companies didn't say when such products might become
available. High-definition television sets -- which offer
crisper pictures and sound than today's standard televisions
-- are already on sale in Japan, and regular commercial
broadcasting is expected to begin later this year.
   The agreement is ironic because Sony and Matsushita have
been major protagonists in a bitter decade-long battle for
the shape of commercial video technology.
   Matsushita-endorsed VHS prevailed over Sony's Betamax in
the first generation of home video machines. Sony is now
pushing its compact 8mm tapes as a better format than VHS for
personal video recording.
   "The three companies had each been conducting their own
research but have combined their latest technologies," the
statement said.
</TEXT>
