<LEADPARA>  Q I am looking for a compact-disc laser lens cleaner. My problem is, I have a
six-disc cartridge-type player from Magnavox. The few lens cleaners that I
have found are recommended only for single-disc players.;    I have been told
that the lens should be cleaned every 10 hours to prevent skipping. Is this
true?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SIMPLE TIPS FOR CLEANING, REPAIRING COMPACT
DISCS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Consumer
the Gadget Guru  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     A Mike Piehl, marketing manager for compact disc players at Magnavox, says
his company offers a single disc tray (item No. SBC3591) as an option for your
unit. It sells for $20. Once this is installed, you can use any laser lens
cleaner available in audio stores.;    However, Piehl adds he typically does
not recommend that customers repair or clean the lenses themselves. If your
discs are skipping, first clean the disc. If the skipping persists, take the
unit to a factory-authorized service center for repair.;    Also, if you have
compact discs that are badly scratched, you might want to check out Memorex's
new Compact Disc Repair and Maintenance Kit. It includes 12 packets of repair
polish and cleaning fluid that work with an ultra-fine, abrasive paper
(similar to sandpaper) that cleans and restores scratched discs.;    Each kit
can restore up to 24 CDs and sells for $15. It is available from J &amp; R Music
World, (800) 221-8180.;    Q I am looking for a timing device similar to a
parking meter that I could attach to a television.;    My plan is to use this
gadget to take tokens (quarters) and thereby place a cost incentive on the
time my children spend watching television. This device could be mechanical or
electronic. If something like that is not available, I would be happy to find
a unit that monitors the amount of time that the television is on. Any ideas?;
   A Although I have yet to find a parking-meter-type gadget for the
television, last summer, I wrote about a child-proof power lock called The
Switch ($20). It attaches to a television's power cord and requires a key to
turn the TV on or off. For more information on The Switch, call (800)
535-5845.;    Q I take exception to your article on the VHS-C video cameras
and tapes. You wrote that "VHS-C tapes can only record 30 minutes." Wrong! I
own a VHS-C camera, and a T-20 tape will record up to one hour on the super
long play mode. The new tapes, T-30s, will record either 30 minutes on
standard play or 90 minutes on SLP.;    To me, the biggest advantage of VHS-C
is: If I'm going to show people my vacation video, I'm not going to bore them
for a full two hours!;    A When preparing that story, I decided to compare
apples to apples and look at both formats at the full-speed, highest quality
mode.;    The quality of the two-hour 8mm and the quality of the 30-minute
VHS-C are similar at the full-speed mode. However, if you would like, I can
compare the two-hour 8mm to the 90-minute VHS-C (30-minute tape at the slower
speed) and show the superlative quality of the 8mm tape.;    The biggest
advantage to the VHS-C tape is that, with an adapter, it can easily play back
in the home VHS deck. With 8mm, you have to run a cable from the camera to a
VCR or television for playback.;    As for boring your audience, the only
thing I can say is that with 8mm, you have the choice of how long you can
record. And please be aware that 8mm tape is available in shorter lengths also.  </TEXT>
