<DESCRIPT>  VIDEO; EQUIPMENT; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN it comes to camcorders, it's risky for any company to advertise a given
model as the smallest and lightest on the market. No sooner is that claim made
than a rival company is insisting it has an even tinier model.;   So let's not
say that Sony's new CCD-TR51 is the smallest you can find. But it certainly is
the smallest in Sony's "TR" line of subcompact 8mm camcorders. Designers have
shaved down the camera body until it measures 4 1/4 inches wide by 4 inches
high by 6 5/8 inches deep. It's about the size of a 35mm still camera.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FOR CAMCORDER FANS, SMALLER IS BETTER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  VIDEO  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     More dramatic is the weight reduction. The earlier TRs weighed 1.7 pounds
without battery and cassette. That's extremely light, but the new model is a
real featherweight at just 1.3 pounds.;   The arrival of the TR51 (about
$1,000) is further evidence that the majority of video shoppers are forsaking
the old idea that bigger is better.;   Goodbye to bulk; For years, the
comparatively bulky VHS camcorders dominated sales. They had the look of
heavy-duty equipment, so serious in purpose that their operators could be
mistaken for TV news crews.;   In comparison, the mini-camcorders that used
8mm and Compact VHS tape appeared toylike, with tiny lenses and control
buttons. Buyers wondered how these baby camcorders could possibly perform as
well as heftier models.;   At first, some of them couldn't. Engineers made the
mistake of making designs too basic. But in the last few years, progress in
miniaturization has brought all the most popular features to the compact
camcorder, and the consumer has responded decisively: Small is indeed
beautiful.;   Consider the latest statistics from the Electronic Industries
Association, which tracks such things. In July 1990, total camcorder sales
were split about evenly between full-size VHS models and the two mini-formats
(8mm and Compact VHS). In July 1991, full-size camcorders fell to about 31
percent while 8mm and Compact VHS shared in 69 percent of sales. In fact, for
the last four months, sales of compact formats garnered 70 percent of sales.; 
 Sony, which expects to sell more than 4 million camcorders this year, can
take much of the credit for the turnaround, and the TR51 is a good example of
why. Despite its size, it still can offer hi-fi stereo recording, a variable
high-speed shutter (six settings), 6:1 power zoom, "world clock" time/date
stamp that can be quickly adjusted for time-zone changes, digital
super-imposer (for creating your own titles) and a remote control.;   Erase to
the finish; It also has the single most valuable feature for efficient
editing: a "flying erase" head that allows for glitch-free stops and starts
between scenes.;   Sony and other manufacturers are continuing to prove that a
camcorder that can fit in your palm is not a toy, but a pocket-size TV studio.  </TEXT>
