   TOKYO -- Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. threw its
considerable weight behind Philips Electronics N.V. in the
battle with Sony Corp. to shape the future consumer audio
market.
   Matsushita said it would help develop and produce
Philips-designed digital compact cassettes -- a product
similar to the common cassette tape but which can record and
play a much higher quality sound.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We decided to support the digital compact cassette
because it seems the most promising successor of the
cassette," a Matsushita spokesman said. He wouldn't say when
the technology will hit the market, but Philips has said it
plans to introduce a product in 1992. Matsushita, the giant
consumer electronics company, sells products under the
National, Panasonic, Technics and Quasar brands.
   The Matsushita decision had been expected in the industry,
but company officials refused to confirm such plans until
last week. The announcement comes less than two months after
Sony made its own claim that it had developed a replacement
for the conventional cassette -- the Mini Disc, a small
compact disk that can record as well as play sound, expected
to go on sale by the end of next year.
   Matsushita's move seems to further damp the future of the
digital-audio tape, or DAT, another technology once hailed
industrywide as the next-generation cassette. The
digital-audio tape got bogged down in battles with the
recording industry, which was worried that the
superior-sounding equipment would trigger a wave of bootleg
copies.
   Matsushita, as well as Sony, has invested heavily in the
digital-audio tape technology, but now "we think DAT is for
high-end professional audio, while digital compact cassettes
are for consumer use," the Matsushita spokesman said. Digital
compact cassette players can play regular cassettes, while
DAT players cannot.
   The key characteristic of all three technologies --
Philips's digital compact cassette, Sony's Mini Disc, and DAT
-- is that they record and play sound digitally, which is a
clearer, more efficient method than the analog format used on
conventional tapes. The improved method offers the same sound
enhancement that compact disks provide over records; the
industry consensus is that technology and demand will lead to
the same transition in tapes.
   But the companies differ over exactly what format
consumers will prefer. Sony's Mini Disc allows users to
access quickly any song, just like a compact disk player. But
it requires users to buy new equipment and disks. Digital
compact cassettes require the cumbersome rewinding and
fastforwarding of tapes, but they won't require consumers to
replace their existing tape libraries.
   "We believe both formats can exist in the market," a Sony
spokeswoman said.
   But some analysts and industry officials argue that one
approach will ultimately become dominant -- and Matsushita's
endorsement helps the digital compact cassette. Although Sony
is considered more innovative than Matsushita, it doesn't
have the same clout to set industry standards. Indeed,
Matsushita's support in the early 1980s for the VHS
video-tape format was a key factor in the demise of Sony's
competing Betamax format.
   "This is a major positive for Philips and the digital
compact cassette," said Jeffrey Zavattero, a consumer
electronics analyst in Tokyo for Jardine Fleming Securities
Ltd. "It's a major negative for Sony, the Mini Disc and DAT."
</TEXT>
