<LEADPARA>  ORION Home Video will release a series of recent films in the extended-play
video mode retailing for a bargain-basement price of $7.98.;    It will be the
first time a major video label has released major studio titles in the EP
mode. Most films are released to video in the standard-play mode, which offers
higher-quality images and audio while running at a faster speed.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VIDEOTAPES FOR $7.98: LET THE BUYER BEWARE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  AUDIO VIDEO  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Orion "Extended-Play Promotion" comprises six recent titles: "Bull
Durham," "Throw Momma From the Train," "Dirty Rotten Scoundrels," "Married to
the Mob," "Frog" and "The Couch Trip.";    While videophiles say the faster,
standard-speed (SP) videocassettes are better in quality, Orion spokesman Paul
Wagner denied there was a quality difference.;    Although playback of the EP
tapes may require an adjustment to the VCR's tracking dial, "there will be no
significant loss of quality in the EP mode," Wagner said.;    But Andy Delle,
chief engineer at the Varitel Video post-production facility in Los Angeles,
said: "There's no question that, regardless of the equipment you play it on, a
film recorded at EP will be of significantly lower (visual) quality than one
recorded at SP.";    The EP mode generally is used by VCR owners to record
programming off television, although it has been used in some low-budget,
public-domain video offerings. (The popular 120 VHS blank tape plays for two
hours in the SP setting and six hours in the EP mode.);    EP product stickers
will carry the message: "Recorded in EP mode, minor tracking adjustments may
be desired.";    The six titles in the Orion promotion will remain available
at standard speed, Orion said.;    Q When will the video companies release
more movies on Super VHS?;    A There are still too few people who own Super
VHS VCRs to interest the studios in the format, and the situation won't change
soon. Although S-VHS has been around since 1987, fewer than 30 movies are
available. The latest is "Misery," coming July 11 at $39.95. For a complete
list, write to Super Source Video, Box 410777, San Francisco 94141, or call
(800) 331-6304.;    Q When I copy a tape from my camcorder the quality
deteriorates considerably. Would a signal booster or anything else improve the
quality?;    A Generally, the first copy from an original sacrifices about 10
percent of the picture clarity. Video enhancers, available from many
manufacturers at many prices, can reduce but not eliminate the loss.;    If
possible, experiment with one on approval before you buy it, or patronize a
store that allows returns.  </TEXT>
