<LEADPARA>  Japanese electronics giant JVC has developed a VHS video cassette recorder
with digital sound that can match or surpass the quality of compact discs --
but consumers outside Japan will have to wait.;   JVC said today it will begin
selling the HR-Z1, the world's first consumer VHS machine with digital sound,
in Japan in December for about $2,250. But officials said they have no plans
for sales overseas.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VCR HAS DIGITAL SOUND  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     'It's rather expensive'; "It's still rather expensive, and our subsidiaries
in other countries said they weren't interested until the price comes down,"
said Tasuku Tachi, general manager for engineering in JVC's Video Products
Division.;   In a presentation today, the VCR demonstrated the benefits of
digital sound recording -- absolute silence in quiet portions, superb dynamic
range and no audible distortion.;   Tachi said JVC decided to develop the
machine because of the growing availability of high-quality audio and video
sources, such as satellite broadcasting in Japan.;   Offers satellite tuner;
The machine includes a built-in satellite tuner. Two Japanese networks use
satellites to broadcast television programs with digital sound, which the new
VCRs can record directly, guaranteeing a virtually perfect recording.;  
However, direct digital recordings from compact discs will not be possible,
since CDs sample sound at 44,100 times per second, while digital VHS offers a
choice of 32,000 or 48,000 times.;   Digital audio tape recorders can record
at all three sampling rates, but contain a circuit called a serial copy
management system that blocks them from making digital copies from other
copies to prevent record piracy.;   "We see this as primarily a video system
rather than an audio system, so at the present time we don't plan to include
any copy management system," Tachi said.  </TEXT>
