<LEADPARA>  A war is shaping up in the music industry, and the battleground is the
cassette tape player.;    Rival groups are tussling over competing
technologies for next-generation cassettes that offer the superior sound
quality of compact discs.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WAR'S BREWING -- ON THE MUSIC FRONT
BATTLE SEEN OVER COMPETING DIGITAL TAPES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     In one camp are several Japanese companies, including Sony Corp., which
began selling digital audiotape products in this country last year. DATs are
about half the size of conventional cassettes but far more expensive.;    The
new contender is N.V. Philips, the Dutch electronics maker, which unveiled a
technology Wednesday it calls the digital compact cassette.;    Unlike the
Japanese DAT players, Philips says machines using its technology will be able
to play today's cassettes as well as the new digital tapes.;    "With the
average household already owning between 50 and 60 music cassettes, this
compatibility is seen as a major factor in the successful introduction of
DCC," Philips said in a statement.;    However, the Philips machines won't be
able to play the Japanese DATs. That means the rivalry could end up a replay
of the videotape war of the 1980s in which the VHS tape format beat out Sony's
Beta standard, leaving millions of consumers with virtually obsolete Beta
tapes and videocassette recorders.;    "What this means for the market is
confusion," said Ivan Berger, technical editor of Audio magazine. "This has
become a very interesting time for the home recording industry because there
are all of these things unsettled.";    Philips says its tape players should
cost $500 to $600 when they are introduced next year -- far less than the
Japanese DAT models, which carry a list price of up to about $1,000.;   
However, industry experts say the price of DAT machines may have dropped
steeply by that point, if the price drops seen in other electronics products
such as VCRs and compact disc players are a guide.;    Both the Japanese and
the Philips technologies record music in digital format, the computer language
used by compact discs, eliminating the background hiss and other distortions
of conventional tape.;    Philips, which invented the cassette tape and the
compact disc, has joined with Tandy Corp., the Fort Worth, Texas-based owner
of the Radio Shack chain, to develop DCC. Although the two companies said in
October they were working on the technology, they waited until Wednesday to
display it at the Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas, the semiannual
showcase for the home electronics industry.;    Tandy says it will make tape
players and blank cassettes at its U.S. plants for sale at Radio Shack stores
and elsewhere. Philips, which makes electronics products under the Magnavox,
Sylvania, Norelco and Philips brands, also will sell home, car and portable
tape players using the technology.;    In addition, Philips says it will
license the technology to other companies and is in advanced discussions with
several Japanese electronics companies, but it would not identify them.;   
"Just as we did with compact disc, we expect the DCC standard will become the
new worldwide standard for this medium," said Wim Wielens, managing director
of Philips' worldwide audio business.;    However, Philips and Tandy deny they
are trying to depose DAT. They say they envision DCC machines appealing to the
mass consumer market, while DAT machines will be favored by audiophiles and
music industry professionals.;    That's due in part to the fact that the DCC
machines will play conventional cassettes, but also is a recognition that DAT
machines already are entrenched in the professional and high-end audio market,
Berger said.;    In addition, DAT machines should continue to appeal to
professionals because they make an exact copy of a digital source, such as a
compact disc, he said. DCC copies do not include all the digital information
from the source, though Philips says the change is not noticeable to the
listener.;    Berger said the ultimate success of the two technologies may be
determined by the recording industry as it decides which formats to use.
Without a substantial number of titles available in the DCC format, the
technology could face an uphill climb.;    Already, a number of major record
companies, including Warner, BMG, EMI and PolyGram -- which is partially owned
by Philips -- have said they are interested in the DCC format, while not
ruling out DAT.;    Sony had no comment on the Philips technology "since none
of us has seen it," said Shari Haber, a spokeswoman for Sony Corp. of
America.;    Like DAT, the DCC technology will limit the ability of consumers
to make copies -- a safeguard demanded by the music industry, which feared it
would lose sales of compact discs. The copy protection technology allows users
to tape a CD, but not to make a copy of that tape.;    Debate over copy
protection delayed the U.S. introduction of DAT machines for almost four years.  </TEXT>
