<LEADPARA>  THE incredible shrinking video camcorder will be disappearing into pockets and
palms this fall.;   A couple of weeks ago, Sony introduced the CCD-TR51, a
1.3-pound stereo-sound and color-picture shooter billed as "the smallest and
lightest 8mm Handycam camcorder." November deliveries are promised on this
baby, which measures a scant 4 1/4 by 4 by 6 5/8 inches. Now reaching our
shores is Sony's not-much-bigger CCD-TR81, the first travel model to exploit
the sharper Hi8 picture-shooting technology, weighing in at one pound, 12
ounces.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CAMCORDERS SHRINK FOR THE NO-HERNIA '90S  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  VIDEO  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Sony's boasts of diminutive proportions had to be Handycam-brand specific,
knowing that a few days later Canon would unveil its new ultraslim UC1 8mm
camcorder with eight-time zoom lens, weighing 1.28 pounds; as well as a more
advanced UCS1, a Hi8 variation with 10-time zoom, eight-position custom
exposure wheel and stereo sound, which bounces the scale to just 1.68 pounds.;
  Slim and packable;   Hitachi's newly unveiled VME25A 8mm camcorder is
slightly heavier, but employs a "twist-and-shoot" folding lens/viewfinder
(previously seen in VHS-C models) that makes this model even slimmer and more
packable than the flat-sided Canon cams. To boot, the Hitachi features an
extraordinary 64-time zoom lens, achieved with digital technology that blows
up the center portion of a captured image.;   Clearly, the smaller-is-better
logic is gaining steam. Early adaptors to video shooting have had it with
their clunky, hernia-producing seven- to 11-pound VHS and Betamovie
camcorders. And first-time buyers are marveling that these new models aren't
much bigger than their 35mm still cameras. Small 8mm and almost as compact
VHS-C camcorders are expected to monopolize sales in the still-lively
electronics market this holiday season.;   But is the very smallest really the
best? Not for everyone. For starters, you'll pay significantly more for the
privilege of carrying less -- $999 or thereabouts at a discount store for the
three new standard 8mm models mentioned above, and around $1,500 for the Hi8
variations (which also demand expensive tape for best pictures).;   If you can
live with one extra pound and a bit more bulk in a camcorder, you'll find lots
of other 8mm and VHS-C models selling in the $750-$799 range, some offered
complete with carrying cases.;   Why is less more costly in a camcorder?
You're essentially paying off the R&amp;D costs in downsizing the chassis, head
drum and circuitry. You're getting first crack at technical improvements to
the species, including more refined focus and exposure monitoring. In all
these mite-y new models, you can run the show and be in it -- with an infrared
remote control so small it can slip into your shirt pocket, or hang discretely
on the gripside of the camcorder (on the Canons) or hide inside the tape lid
(on the Hitachi).;   Bigger can be better;   Those bigger models have their
pluses, too. In a recent hands-on comparison of the Sony "Family" series
CCD-F401 (two pounds, 10 ounces) and the small, Hi8 CCD-TR81, I found the F401
more user-friendly on several accounts. Its buttons and labels are larger and
better spaced, easier to read and locate by touch. The bigger-barreled lens on
the F401 went wider (giving a more expansive view) and tighter (in the
telephoto mode) than the TR81's lens, though both are billed as eight-time
zooms. There are extra functions on the F401's larger remote control,
including slow motion and full record from stop.;   Best of all, the F401
offers a sports viewfinder with a magnified image so big you can stand a foot
or two away from the camcorder and still monitor the recording! This feature's
great for following the action of a sporting event or school play. When forced
to keep one eye closed and the other glued to a viewfinder, it's easy to lose
the big(ger) picture.;   As Sony's new high-end model, the CCD-TR81 certainly
has plenty to recommend itself, besides delightfully diminutive proportions.
Shooting inside under artificial light (the toughest test for a camcorder),
its Hi8 recording produced a cleaner, more detailed and color-accurate
picture. The TR81's stereo sound recording was smoother and more realistic
than the F401's monaural track. I also relished the TR81's unique, flywheel
adjustment control for brightness and shutter speed, which lets you make
recording adjustments in a wink.  </TEXT>
