<HEAD>Have Yourself a Video Christmas - On a Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's more than one way to change a channel.
Here's a penny-pincher's guide - well, sort of - to a merry, video
Christmas for you and your loved ones:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE BIG TICKET:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   - Stereo VCR. This one piece of hardware should be as central to
your home video system as the TV tube itself. It's much more
versatile and it's the easiest purchase to justify.
   A stereo VCR converts any television into a stereo TV by
delivering its right and left audio channels to your home audio
system. It's the biggest, cheapest single improvement you can make
to a conventional TV.
   With the stereo VCR hooked up and tuned in and your good old
19-inch black-and-white Philco between the speakers, you have
stereo TV.
   It gives you much finer acoustic detail to go along with the
video image, and you'll be surprised at how much a good soundtrack
enhances your viewing.
   And there's a lot to hear: Most major TV markets have more than
one stereo broadcaster, most cable systems can deliver a stereo
signal, and most videocassettes sold and rented today are in
stereo.
   With that much programming available, it's just foolish not to
upgrade.
   When you're shopping, remember: A ``two-head'' or ``four-head''
or ``Hi-Fi'' VCR isn't necessarily a stereo model. Every VCR needs
one tape head to play and one head to record. Four-head models
allow for slow-motion, freeze frames and other special effects.
   With a stereo VCR, you also get SAP, or Secondary Audio Program
services (also known as MTS or Multi-Channel Television Sound). PBS
stations use it for descriptive narrative, weather reports and
simultaneous translation to a second language.
   Full-featured models retail for $300 to $450, but basic models
can be had for less than $250.
   - Stereo TV monitor. Here's where shopping pays. Discounters
offer stereo-ready, 25-inch TV monitors for just less than $400,
and basic 27-inch models for just more than $400. These are just
about perfect for home viewing.
   This is where belt-tightening gets tough, because the more bells
and whistles you tack on to that basic picture tube, the faster
that big ticket fattens.
   Then you find yourself paying $50 for delivery of a $2,500,
35-inch behemoth that claims to have 700 lines of resolution,
picture-in-picture, ``super-woofer'' and a microwave popcorn maker.
   Singlehandedly, you have tipped the economy into recession and
yourself into debtor's prison.
   And that bigger tube whets your appetite for that sweet, $500
LaserDisc player that has a 60 percent sharper picture, letterbox
formats, CD sound and handles audio Compact Discs - a whole new way
to spend money!
   Be strong (or at least have the decency to wait for the
after-Christmas sales).
   - Video Player. This is the biggest bargain for a budget.
Discounters offer rugged, play-only VHS machines for less than
$150. For the simple pleasure of home video viewing, they're hard
to beat.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE LESSER TICKET:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   - A decoder. Yes, that $1,500 ``Surround-Sound'' loudspeaker
system would match your living room decor, but Radio Shack sells
the basic decoder for around $130. So you find a couple of extra
speakers, hook 'em up, rent your favorite disaster movie, and strap
yourself to the couch. ... Apartment dwellers note: THIS DOES NOT
INDEMNIFY YOU FROM PLASTER DAMAGE!
   - A cassette rewinder. For about $30, you can spare the
wear-and-tear that sends most VCR and players to the shop.
   - LaserDiscs. Got a finicky videophile on your list? These
beauties sell for anywhere from $19.95 red tag specials to $200
boxed sets, although most releases retail for $30 to $35. Give 'em
``Motel Hell.'' That scene with the dueling chainsaws is high point
of 20th century cinema. Heh, heh, heh. ...
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE LOW TICKET:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   - Multiple-outlet strips. Anyone with electronic gear will
welcome one of these. At $20 to $30, a four- or six-outlet strip
feeds into a safe, heavy-duty cord and a three-prong plug.
   - Spike protector. At about $20, it can prevent a lightning bolt
from frying a home entertainment center.
   - Prerecorded cassettes. There are thousands of movies on the
home market, and you already know what movies and stars your
friends and relatives enjoy. And is there a better way to
tranquilize the kids late on Christmas Day than a movie on
cassette? Lassie, come home!
   - Blank tapes. In the history of videocassette recording, no one
ever has been known to have enough blank tapes. No one. Ever.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE LITTLEST TICKET:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   - Compressed air. A spray can of this sure beats dusting with
Lemon Pledge. - A good penlight. Fumbling in the dark for tiny
switches, wires and RCA sockets is not unlike hell.
   - Videotape labels. Quick, which is it: SIS-'N'-MOM '86, VAC`N
H'LITES '85, NATIONAL VELVET. New labels mean never having to say
you're sorry.
   Happy holidays!
</TEXT>
