<HEAD>JVC, MCA Announce Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victor Co. of Japan said Monday it will create a
new record company with the music division of the U.S.
entertainment giant MCA.
   The new company, formed between JVC and MCA Music Entertainment
Group, will market and promote the record labels MCA, Geffen and
GRP in Japan, according to a statement from JVC, manufacturer of a
wide range of audio equipment, records, compact discs.
   JVC spokesman Masayuki Murakami said the move was not related to
reports of a buyout of MCA by JVC's parent company, the consumer
electronics giant Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.
   Murakami said the agreement will cover records and compact
discs; music videos were under negotiation. Among the artists that
record under the three labels are Tom Petty, Guns 'n Roses,
Aerosmith and Chick Corea.
   The deal gives Matsushita access to audio software while helping
MCA market its products in Japan, said Barry Dargan, senior
technology analyst at James Capel &amp; Co.
   The new venture, which will be owned equally by the two
companies and begin operations next year, also could help JVC
develop a market for digital audio tape, or DAT.
   Murakami said MCA approached JVC about the record deal, and
negotiations began last spring.
   ``As far as our talks with MCA are concerned, it was ... nothing
related to Matsushita talks with MCA,'' Murakami said.
   Last week, Matsushita confirmed it was holding talks with MCA
but refused to elaborate. Reports said the Japanese company was
considering a buyout of MCA, which includes Universal Pictures,
valued at $7 billion.
   Last year, rival Sony Corp. acquired Columbia Pictures
Entertainment, in large part to gain control over its rich library
of old films and television shows.
   Purchases of film libraries allow consumer electronics companies
to release old movies and television shows for the videotape
recorders they manufacture, and also provide material for future
high-definition television recordings.
   JVC originated the VHS video format, while Sony is a strong
backer of 8-millimeter video.
</TEXT>
