<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Sony's color Watchman model FDL-330S has a 2.7-inch detachable
screen that can double as a camcorder monitor.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION; PRODUCT; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  MINIATURE television sets are most plentiful at ball games, I am told, their
antennas sprouting from the stands. After a particularly dramatic touchdown or
double play, heads bend toward them as if in benediction.;    The screens are
tuned not to favorite soap operas and sitcoms but to the very same game being
played on the field.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MEGA AND MINI TVS ARE CHANGING THE WAY WE
LIVE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Home Electronics  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Such a peculiar combination of public gathering and private viewing, of an
experience mixed with the televised image of it, is one consequence of the
successful new crop of television sets the size of shirt pockets.;    At the
other extreme is the new generation of large-screen TV sets -- 30 inches or
more, measured diagonally. They, too, are objects of near-obsession, not only
dominating rooms but nearly replacing them.;    When a 50-inch screen comes to
life, conversation stops and eyes turn.;    One new model can simultaneously
display still images from seven different programs, create a stroboscopic
array of three pictures and split the screen in half to show two channels at
once.;    Sets of these extreme sizes were a small percentage of the 20
million sold last year, but they are gradually leading to new relationships
with the medium.;    TV's changing role;  Just as the era of network dominance
is coming to an end, so is TV's mooring in home life. The large screen creates
a sort of video cocoon that absorbs viewers in silence: The home is virtually
incidental.;    The miniature model severs the TV set from home life almost
completely: Watching television alone can now be a public act, something done
in the park, a library, a sports stadium.;    One could almost feel nostalgic
for the days when the TV set was a modern version of the kitchen hearth, its
blue light the center of the domestic world.;    The miniature TV set was
developed by Sony seven years ago, a video version of the Walkman, the
personal tape player. They dubbed it the Watchman and have since sold 3
million of them.;    Sony says a third have been sold to sports fans, who take
them to games to catch the commentary and instant replays.;    Sony's most
inexpensive model, the FD-10A, has a two-inch black-and-white screen and sells
for less than $100. Another, aimed specifically at sports fans, comes with a
shoulder strap (the FD-250; it lists at $169.99 and also can be hooked up to a
camcorder).;    Sony, among other Japanese companies, also is now producing
color models (beginning at $399), and have sold about 100,000 in the last
three years.;    The color LCD screens are far superior to those available a
few years ago, though they still have limited viewing angles, making one
viewer seem company and two a crowd.;    Recently, energy has been focused on
redesigning the shells for these screens. Sony's color Watchman model FDL-330S
is in the shape of a cube with a 2.7-inch detachable screen that can double as
a camcorder monitor.;    This spring, Sharp is to release the largest
mini-set, which will have a 5.6-inch screen; Sharp shows it in publicity
photographs installed in a car, pointed toward the passenger seat, and says it
can withstand the temperature variations of an automobile's interior.;   
Casio's new pocket set (TV-470) will have rounded corners and thumb-controlled
buttons, making it seem more like a hand-held video game.;    The video-game
companies, in turn, are making hand-held game players that double as TV sets.
NEC has just created a color game player, the Turbo Express ($249), which
accepts Turbografx-16 cards for play on its 2.7-inch screen.;    It also
offers an optional tuner ($100) that turns the game player into a television
set. Sega is about to follow suit with a new hand-held system, Game Gear.;   
Other electronic crossbreeds also have been evolving. Two years ago, Sony
combined one of its Watchman color screens with an 8-millimeter videocassette
recorder to create the Video Walkman.;    The latest version (GV-300, $1,400),
about a year old, is the size of a hard-cover book, and some fear it may one
day replace books.;    This Walkman has a tiltable four-inch screen and stereo
programmable recording. It can even be hooked up to a large-screen set and
used as an ordinary VCR.;    Everyday uses;    Sony, which owns Columbia
Pictures, is promising extensive releases of movies on tape for the compact
format.;    Businesses are using the Video Walkman for training tapes, and
Virgin Atlantic Airways provides passengers with them for movie-viewing.;   
They can even be rented (for $10 a day, with a movie) from Grand Central Radio
in Manhattan. In Japan, the Video Walkman has inspired the notion of "video
magazines" for commuters, mailed to subscribers periodically.;    Other
companies also released small screens with VCRs last year. Panasonic makes a
lunch-box-size player that accepts full-size VHS tapes (PV-M429) and shows
them on a four-inch screen. Sharp's $1,249 VHS tape player (VC-V540U) allows
TV viewing as well.;    All the while, large-screen models are improving in
sales as well as in resolution and brightness. The trade journal Television
Digest said that in the first nine months of 1990 -- a year when color-set
sales fell almost 5 percent -- sales of televisions with traditional color
tubes larger than 30 inches jumped more than 50 percent; nearly 200,000 units
were shipped to dealers.;    Shipments of projection sets, which can have
screens 50 inches or larger and range in price from $3,000 to $5,000, leaped
more than 25 percent to almost 270,000 units.;    All of this is bound to have
an effect on the way television is watched and even programmed. The small
screens make TV seem peculiarly distant.;    Sensory stimulation is minimized;
the music is bottled and strained. One watches TV programs and movies more
casually, only for the essentials. The broad outlines of plot and character
and motion become paramount.;    Large screens seem to do just the opposite,
turning soap commercials into epics. The camera movements become grandly
stylized.;    The music thuds its way into the stomach. Facial features of
sitcom characters start to take on the heroic dimensions once reserved for the
silver screen.;    Casual watching becomes almost impossible, movies become
irresistible and the trivial gets the same treatment as the momentous. Nothing
else can compete, certainly not the home.;    No doubt, the home will survive
the indignity. In the meantime, Sharp's solution, still in its technological
infancy, is enticing: its $3,495 Sharpvision XV-100, the first LCD projection
television set.;    It looks like a small movie projector without the reels
and, weighing 30 pounds, can sit on a table or be carried from room to room.; 
  When hooked up to a tuner or VCR or disk player it can project adjustable
images -- from 20 to 100 inches -- on any wall or screen. It can make
television seem both portable and theatrical.  </TEXT>
